  "model": "gpt-4o-mini",
  "response_text": "Recovering from burnout and low energy requires a gentle approach that focuses on nourishing the body, mind, and spirit. Below is a weekly diet and workout routine designed to support recovery, enhance energy levels, and promote overall well-being. Always consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new diet or exercise program, especially if you have pre-existing health conditions.\n\n### Weekly Diet Plan\n\n#### General Guidelines:\n- Focus on whole, nutrient-dense foods.\n- Stay hydrated; aim for at least 8 cups of water per day.\n- Eat smaller, more frequent meals to maintain energy levels.\n- Incorporate a variety of colors in fruits and vegetables.\n\n#### Daily Meals:\n**Breakfast Options:**\n1. Overnight oats with chia seeds, almond milk, and topped with berries and nuts.\n2. Smoothie with spinach, banana, protein powder, almond butter, and almond milk.\n3. Greek yogurt with honey, walnuts, and sliced apple.\n\n**Snack Ideas:**\n- A piece of fruit (banana, apple, or orange).\n- Handful of mixed nuts or seeds.\n- Veggie sticks (carrots, cucumber, bell peppers) with hummus.\n\n**Lunch Options:**\n1. Quinoa salad with mixed greens, chickpeas, cherry tomatoes, cucumber, and lemon dressing.\n2. Whole grain wrap with turkey or hummus, spinach, and sliced veggies.\n3. Lentil soup with a side of whole grain bread.\n\n**Snack Ideas:**\n- Rice cakes with almond butter.\n- Cottage cheese with pineapple.\n- Dark chocolate square (70% cacao or higher).\n\n**Dinner Options:**\n1. Grilled salmon with steamed broccoli and sweet potato.\n2. Stir-fried tofu with mixed vegetables and brown rice.\n3. Baked chicken breast with quinoa and roasted Brussels sprouts.\n\n**Hydration:**\n- Herbal teas (e.g., chamomile, peppermint) or infuse water with fruits.\n- Limit caffeine and alcohol, especially in the recovery phase.\n\n### Weekly Workout Routine\n\n#### General Guidelines:\n- Focus on low-impact exercises that promote relaxation and energy restoration.\n- Incorporate activities that you enjoy to make it sustainable.\n- Aim for 30 minutes of movement most days, with rest days as needed.\n\n#### Weekly Schedule:\n\n**Monday: Gentle Yoga (30 minutes)**\n- Focus on restorative poses and deep breathing.\n\n**Tuesday: Nature Walk (30-45 minutes)**\n- Walk at a comfortable pace in a park or green space.\n\n**Wednesday: Strength Training (Bodyweight) (30 minutes)**\n- Squats, push-ups (modified if needed), lunges, and planks.\n- 2 sets of 10-12 reps for each exercise, focusing on form and control.\n\n**Thursday: Restorative Yoga or Stretching (30 minutes)**\n- Emphasize flexibility and deep relaxation.\n\n**Friday: Light Cardio (30 minutes)**\n- Choose an activity like cycling, swimming, or brisk walking at a comfortable pace.\n\n**Saturday: Mindful Movement (30 minutes)**\n- Tai chi, Pilates, or dance class focusing on enjoyment and movement quality.\n\n**Sunday: Rest or Gentle Activity**\n- Free day for rest, meditation, or gentle stretching.\n\n### Additional Tips for Recovery:\n- Prioritize sleep; aim for 7-9 hours each night.\n- Practice mindfulness or meditation to reduce stress.\n- Consider journaling to process thoughts and feelings.\n- Engage in hobbies or activities that bring joy and fulfillment.\n\n### Conclusion\nRecovery from burnout is a gradual process, so be patient and kind to yourself. Adjust the diet and workout routine as needed to fit your personal preferences and energy levels. Listening to your body is key to ensuring a sustainable and effective recovery journey.",
